WEBEX/TEAMS INSTABILITY

We are receiving numerous reports of instability when connecting to Webex and/or Microsoft Teams today. We have learned of multiple internet service provider outages in the NJ/NY area along with other network connectivity providers. We do not currently have information as to when these services are expected to be restored.

We thank you for your patience.

ATTENTION HYBRID FAMILIES: All parents of students receiving in-person instruction are required to complete the WTPS COVID-19 Parent Daily Screening Pledge for Students PRIOR to students attending school. • For directions on accessing the pledge in your Unified Classroom Parent Account, click this link: https://www.wtps.org/cms/lib/NJ01912980/Centricity/Domain/168/Parent%20Instructions%20fo%20COVID%20Pledge%209-9-2020.pdf.

post_text:
Cooper Hospital Donates 1,500 Cloth Face Masks to District

Cooper Hospital representative Jeff Miller stopped by the Washington Township Public Schools’ Central Administration Building on August 26th with a donation of 1,500 cloth face masks for use in the schools.

“We are so grateful to the folks at Cooper Hospital for including our District in their generous gesture,” Superintendent of Schools Joe Bollendorf said. “We will make them available to families in need as masks will be required on all school buses and in all of our schools when we resume face-to-face learning.”
text:

post_text:
Washington Township Families:

All cohort assignments were released to parents earlier this afternoon. Please note:

• We, most respectfully, cannot accommodate requests to change in-person cohorts (Cohort A to Cohort B or Cohort B to Cohort A). We also cannot accept requests for Cohort C as it is specific to special programming. We apologize for this inconvenience and certainly understand this may create some challenges, but it is necessary to ensure appropriate social distancing in classes, on the bus, and in specific programs.

• If you did not receive your child’s cohort assignment, please email your child’s building principal. We may just need to update your contact information to ensure you are receiving our communications.

• If you want to request a change of instructional preference such as in-person to remote or remote to in-person, please email your child’s building principal. A friendly reminder that a request to change from remote to in-person instruction may take up to two weeks to accommodate.

As always, your time and attention are most appreciated.

Hello, Washington Township Families. All instructional and transportation preferences submitted via our WTPS Commitment Form or provided to our school staff are now final. If you did not complete the survey or if a district representative did not reach you via phone last week, we have submitted your preference as “in-person” and “requesting transportation” (unless your child is a walker).

From this point forward, we respectfully request that:

• All requests to change instructional preferences (in-person to remote or remote to in-person) be submitted in writing (email will suffice) to the appropriate building principal.
• All transportation requests be submitted in writing to our transportation department to the attention of Ms. O’Donnell (SOdonnell@wtps.org).

Please note that requests to change preferences may take two weeks or more to accommodate so that we can ensure proper programming, appropriate social distancing, etc. Any medical needs or special circumstances will certainly be considered.

From this point forward, we respectfully request that:

• All transportation requests be submitted in writing to our transportation department to the attention of Ms. O’Donnell (SOdonnell@wtps.org).

Please note that requests to change preferences may take two weeks or more to accommodate so that we can ensure proper programming, appropriate social distancing, etc. Any medical needs or special circumstances will certainly be considered.

In Memoriam: Marianne Gehringer

The District mourns the passing of Marianne Gehringer, a dedicated bus driver for more than 30 years. Gehringer proudly raised her five children in Washington Township and cared for every child on her bus as though they were her own. She was a competitive tennis and bridge player. Marianne was always positive, happy and loved life and was a cherished friend to many in our community. We extend our sympathies to the Gehringer family during this difficult time.

Funeral arrangements are below.
https://www.farnellifuneralhome.com/obituary/maryanne-gehringer

post_text:
Hurffville and Wedgwood Elementary School ELEMEnTS Students Conceptualize, Create 3-D Projects

An Apple watch charging station, a Philadelphia sports-themed eyeglass holder, a double pot plant holder, a toothbrush holder, an iPad stand and a host of other creative concepts where imagined and produced by Diane Jablonowski’s fifth-grade ELEMEnTS Program students at Hurffville and Wedgwood Elementary Schools during remote learning this spring.

“My students learned computer-aided design skills using Nearpod and Tinkercard,” Jablonowski said. “They mastered the basics of 3-D printing and then set to work designing and editing their original models. Once editing was complete, I printed their models remotely and delivered the models to the students' home mailboxes. They did a great job. It truly was a remote learning success story.”

post_text:
The District has emailed all families who registered for the Pre-K 3 lottery with their child’s lottery number. If you applied for the lottery and did not receive a lottery email, it may be for one of the following reasons:

-- The child’s birthday was not in the appropriate range (age 3 on or before October 1, 2020).

-- The application was submitted after the deadline (May 28, 2020).

If you met the application requirements, but did not receive an email, kindly contact Brandy Sims at bsims@wtps.org by 3:00 pm on Wednesday, June 3, 2020 and we will be happy to help you! The lottery will take place on Thursday, June 4, 2020 at 5:00 pm on the WTPS Facebook page. Selected families will be contacted shortly after with further information.

post_text:
Washington Township High School Teachers Organize Fundraiser, Pay it Forward

After learning of the extraordinary generosity of the Washington Township community that supported gifts for members of the Washington Township High School Class of 2020 and staff flowers and gifts, WTHS teachers Patti Tsoukalis and Lauren Gallagher organized a fundraiser of their own to “Pay It Forward.”

With the support of District staff members, who contributed cash and gift cards, the two collected $3,155 in donations. All told, the effort raised $1,500 for Mother’s Cupboard, $900 for the school’s TWP pantry and gift cards to local businesses totaling $755.

WTEF Postpones 24th Annual Golf Classic; Hopes to Reschedule Event for Fall

The Washington Township Education Foundation has postponed its 24th Annual Golf Classic, originally scheduled for Friday, June 19, 2020, at White Oaks Country Club, because of ongoing quarantine restrictions due to COVID-19. The Foundation remains optimistic that the fundraiser can be hosted in the fall and will share out a new date if and when it is confirmed. We are grateful for your understanding and ongoing support of the WTEF.

The Washington Township Board of Education will hold its April 28 regular session meeting virtually instead of in person, using the Cisco WebEx platform. Members of the public wishing to listen and/or participate in the meeting can access the virtual meeting through instructions on our website, www.wtps.org. Executive (closed) session starts at 6:30 p.m., with the open, public session starting at 7 p.m.

Members of the public wishing to listen and/or participate in the meeting by Webex may do so by pre-registering via the registration link below. A confirmation email will sent with a link to join the meeting. Detailed instructions for connecting via Webex and via phone can be found in the second link below. And the meeting agenda can be found in the third link.

https://wtps.webex.com/wtps/onstage/g.php?MTID=e2a00e146c8809420a813eabb78f5aa4c

https://www.wtps.org/cms/lib/NJ01912980/Centricity/Domain/4/Public%20Webex%20Directions.pdf

https://go.boarddocs.com/nj/wtps/Board.nsf/vpublic?open#

post_text:
So Happy to See You!

Benjamin Rodrigo, a second-grade student in Diane Zambino’s class at Birches Elementary and the son of Birches teachers Paul and Jen Rodrigo, visited his classmates via the class’ first WebEx meeting on April 24th.

“It was awesome,” Zambino said. “The children had so much fun saying hello to each other. Today was a Show and Share Day. It was also a Birches Spirit Day!”

And a great way to end the week, with a face-to-face hello…and goodbye.

post_text: The District mourns the recent passing of long-time educator and administrator Eli Maslekoff, who worked in Township from 1974 to 2001. In addition to serving as a middle school guidance counselor for many years, he was named director of student personnel services in 1997 and assumed the assistant principal post at Orchard Valley Middle School in November of 2000, until his retirement and relocation to Las Vegas. Eli, a Vietnam veteran, was well-respected and well-liked by staff and students alike, and formed deep and lasting friendships with many in the District, including former superintendent Tom Flemming and middle school colleagues Ron Lucarini and Dominick Temmallo. He was known for his great sense of humor and his caring, kindhearted nature. Please join us in keeping his wife, Diane, and his daughters, Lea and Dana, in your prayers.

post_text:
Starting Monday, New Jersey students in grades 3 through 6 can tune in to public television to follow some of the classroom lessons they've been missing since the statewide closure of schools due to the coronavirus pandemic.

Garden State teachers will be giving lessons on NJTV, the state's public-access network, in an initiative designed to advance remote instruction at home. NJTV, the New Jersey Education Association and the state Department of Education partnered in the effort.

PLEASE NOTE: This information is being shared with our families as a courtesy for those who are looking for supplemental enrichment for their children to enjoy. The NJTV programming does not replace the remote learning that the District is organizing for families and will not be reviewed or graded by District staff.

Please click on the link below to learn more.

https://www.courierpostonline.com/story/news/2020/04/02/nj-offer-home-learning-public-television-amid-coronavirus-crisis/5112798002/

post_text:
GTECC is Staying in Touch with FlipGrid!

Students at Grenloch Terrace Early Childhood Center are staying connected during remote learning. Each day, teachers post a question of the day on FlipGrid. Students and teachers then take turns posting their own video response to the topic. Students can then leave a reply via video response back to their peers. Some topics have been: leave a birthday message for a classmate, tell us a joke, show and tell, how you showed kindness that day, etc. Pictured below are examples from Mrs. Wendi Mailliard and Miss Caitlin Rigby's classes.

post_text:
Live from the Laundry Pile!

Hurffville Elementary School fourth-grade teacher Jacki Tiger is one shining example of the creativity and innovation of Washington Township educators during challenging coronavirus times. Tiger is using her washer and dryer as a white board and is videotaping and streaming math lessons for her students. She has dubbed this educational session "Live from the Laundry Pile!"
text:
Live from the Laundry Pile!

Hurffville Elementary School fourth-grade teacher Jacki Tiger is one shining example of the creativity and innovation of Washington Township educators during challenging coronavirus times. Tiger is using her washer and dryer as a white board and is videotaping and streaming math lessons for her students. She has dubbed this educational session "Live from the Laundry Pile!"

post_text: The Washington Township Board of Education will conduct the Wednesday, March 18th work session starting at 7 p.m.; however, in accordance with social distancing guidelines, the meeting may not exceed 10 persons. Board members will attend virtually, via WebEx, while specific district administration will be present. The Eileen Abbott Central Administration Building will be open for public comment during the meeting, but the room capacity may never exceed 10 persons. Please consider reviewing the agenda online and emailing questions to the Board president, Julie Kozempel (jkozempel@boe.wtps.org), in advance of the meeting. The recorded meeting will be available online via podcast and on channel 9 and 36 after the meeting. Thank you for your understanding.

The New Jersey Department of Education has directed all school districts to create a remote learning plan in the event districts are required to close schools due to potential health-related issues. Districts able to provide this remote instruction may count these days toward the state’s 180-school-day requirement. To that end, we are surveying our community to determine our ability to implement an online learning plan.

The 2020 Washington Township Public Schools’ Student Home Technology Survey will be used to help schools establish these remote learning plans. Please click on the link below to access the survey:

As part of its strategic plan, Washington Township Public Schools plans to conduct a School Climate Survey for all students in grades 4-12. The survey climate logo 2 may be read to younger students, administered in a small group or individually as needed, and allows students to choose picture icons for responses. Data collected will assist the district in identifying areas of strength and areas that need improvement so that we may continue to provide your child with the best educational environment possible.

Click the link below for more information and to grant permission for your child (grades 4-12) to participate in the survey.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/PXYP8JQ

post_text:
Thirteen Washington Township High School seniors recently were recognized as recipients of the 2020 DECA Emerging Leader Award. The award recognizes students studying in marketing, finance, hospitality and management for being an academically prepared, community-oriented, professionally responsible, experienced leader through participation in DECA.

post_text:
Convening for a Chorus Line!

The cast and crew of Washington Township High School's production of "A Chorus Line" posed for a group photo during one of their final dress rehearsals before their performances on Thursday, March 12th and Friday, March 13th at 7:30 p.m. and Saturday, March 14th at 2 p.m. and 7:30 p.m. Tickets can be purchased online at http://wthsnj.booktix.com/ and will be available at the door one hour before each show in the school's 11/12 Play House.
